      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "You are absolutely right that nationalism often functions as an exclusionary \"us vs. them\" mechanism, which is why it frequently leads to conflict. However, I argue that the benefits of national cohesion—such as mobilizing resources for public goods and fostering civic pride—can outweigh the risks if the state actively works to expand the definition of \"us\" to include marginalized groups. The danger lies not in the concept itself, but in the failure of leaders to translate that inclusive vision into tangible policy.",
      "source": "target",
